definition.value: An N(4)-glycosylated L-asparagine residue derived from N(4)-(alpha-D-Man-(1->2)-alpha-D-Man-(1->2)-alpha-D-Man-(1->3)-[alpha-D-Man-(1->3)-[alpha-D-Man-(1->6)]-alpha-D-Man-(1->6)]-beta-D-Man-(1->4)-beta-D-GlcNAc-(1->4)-beta-D-GlcNAc)-L-Asn.
A monohydroxybenzoic acid that is p-salicylic acid with bromo- substituents at C-3 and C-5 of the benzene ring.

An N(4)-glycosylated L-asparagine residue derived from N(4)-(alpha-D-Man-(1->2)-alpha-D-Man-(1->3)-[alpha-D-Man-(1->3)-[alpha-D-Man-(1->6)]-alpha-D-Man-(1->6)]-beta-D-Man-(1->4)-beta-D-GlcNAc-(1->4)-beta-D-GlcNAc)-L-Asn.
A bisammonium salt of a titanium coordination entity in which the titanium central atom is coordinated to two 2-methyl-3-oxobutane-1,4-diyl bidentate ligands and two hydroxy groups.
A calcium salt with the formula CaTiO3, generally obtained in the form of the mineral perovskite.
An agonist that binds to and activates vitamin D receptors

An N(4)-glycosylated L-asparagine residue derived from N(4)-{beta-D-GlcNAc-(1->2)-alpha-D-Man-(1->3)-[beta-D-GlcNAc-(1->4)]-[beta-D-GlcNAc-(1->2)-alpha-D-Man-(1->6)]-beta-D-Man-(1->4)-beta-D-GlcNAc-(1->4)-beta-D-GlcNAc}-L-Asn
A tryptamine alkaloid that is N-methyltryptamine carrying an additional phosphoryloxy substituent at position 4.
An L-glutamine derivative in which one of the side-chain amide hydrogens of L-glutamine has been replaced by a phospho group.

An N(4)-glycosylated L-asparagine residue derived from N(4)-{beta-D-GlcNAc-(1->2)-[beta-D-GlcNAc-(1->4)]-alpha-D-Man-(1->3)-[beta-D-GlcNAc-(1->2)-alpha-D-Man-(1->6)]-beta-D-Man-(1->4)-beta-D-GlcNAc-(1->4)-beta-D-GlcNAc}-L-Asn.
Any glycoside derived from beta-D-galactosyl-(1->3)-N-acetyl-alpha-D-glucosamine

A carbohydrate acid derivative anion obtained by deprotonation of the carboxy group of any alpha-N-acetylneuraminosyl-(2->3)-beta-D-galactosyl-(1->4)-[alpha-L-fucosyl-(1->3)]-N-acetyl-beta-D-glucosaminide

An N(4)-glycosylated L-asparagine residue derived from N(4)-{beta-D-GlcNAc-(1->2)-[beta-D-GlcNAc-(1->4)]-alpha-D-Man-(1->3)-[beta-D-GlcNAc-(1->2)-[beta-D-GlcNAc-(1->6)]-alpha-D-Man-(1->6)]-beta-D-Man-(1->4)-beta-D-GlcNAc-(1->4)-beta-D-GlcNAc}-L-Asn.
A polyanionic polymer obtained by global deprotonation of the carboxy and phosphate groups of reduced coenzyme F420-(gamma-Glu)n. Major microspecies at pH 7.3
An EC 1.3.1.* (oxidoreductase acting on donor CH-CH group, NAD+ or NADP+ as acceptor) inhibitor that interferes with the action of enoyl-[acyl-carrier-protein] reductase (NADH), EC 1.3.1.9.

An N(4)-glycosylated L-asparagine residue derived from N(4)-{beta-D-GlcNAc-(1->2)-[beta-D-GlcNAc-(1->4)]-alpha-D-Man-(1->3)-[beta-D-GlcNAc-(1->2)-[beta-D-GlcNAc-(1->4)]-[beta-D-GlcNAc-(1->6)]-alpha-D-Man-(1->6)]-beta-D-Man-(1->4)-beta-D-GlcNAc-(1->4)-beta-D-GlcNAc}-L-Asn.
A C45 carotenoid that is an intermediate in the biosyntheses of decaprenoxanthin by Corynebacterium glutamicum and gamma-cyclic sarcinaxanthin by Micrococcus luteus.
A C50 carotenoid that is an intermediate in the biosyntheses of decaprenoxanthin by Corynebacterium glutamicum and gamma-cyclic sarcinaxanthin by Micrococcus luteus.
A glycopeptide consisting of the Ara6 epitope attached to an Ala-Asn-Ser-Ser-Phe-Ala-Pro-NH2 heptapeptide via a [(2-hydroxyethoxy)imino]acetyl linker.
A glucan derivative that consists of a (1->4)-beta-D-glucan moiety attached at position 1 of any ceramide via a glycosidic linkage.
An organic anionic group obtained by deprotonation of the phosphate OH groups of (5R)-5,6-dihydro-5-(thymidin-7-yl)thymidine dimer residue; major microspecies at pH 7.3
An organic anionic group obtained by deprotonation of the phosphate OH groups of thymidine dimer residue; major microspecies at pH 7.3
Any phenol that acts as an electron donor.
Any phenoxy radical that acts as an electron donor.
An inositol phosphoceramide obtained by formal condensation of the carboxy group of 2-hydroxyhexacosanoic acid with the amino group of phytosphingosine-1-phospho-(1D-myo-inositol).
A glycopeptide consisting of the Ara6 epitope attached to an Asp-Ala-His-Ala-Thr-Leu-Arg-NH2 heptapeptide via a [(2-hydroxyethoxy)imino]acetyl linker.
A glycopeptide consisting of the Ara6 epitope attached to a Thr-Thr-Tyr-Val-Val-Asn-Pro-NH2 heptapeptide via a [(2-hydroxyethoxy)imino]acetyl linker.

A member of the class of barbiturates that is barbituric acid in which one of the nitrogens (position 1) is substituted by a p-tolyl group while the carbon at position 5 is substituted by a (2E)-3-[p-(dimethylamino)phenyl]allylidene group. It has significant osteogenic activity.

A member of the class of barbiturates that is barbituric acid in which one of the nitrogens (position 1) is substituted by a 3,5-dimethylphenyl group while the carbon at position 5 is substituted by a (2E)-(3-[p-(dimethylamino)phenyl]allylidene group. It has significant osteogenic activity.
An inositol phosphophytoceramide obtained by formal condensation of the carboxy group of any fatty acid with the amino group of inositol-1-phospho-(8E)-phytosphing-8-enine
An inositol phosphomannosylinositol phosphophytoceramide in which the phytoceramide fragment contains 18 carbons.
An inositol phosphomannosylinositol phosphophytoceramide in which the phytoceramide fragment contains 20 carbons.
An inositol phosphomannosylinositol phosphophytoceramide in which the ceramide fragment is specified as N-acylsphinganine.
An inositol phosphomannosylinositol phosphophytoceramide in which the ceramide fragment is specified as N-acyl-C20-sphinganine.
A C32 phosphomycoketide in which all five stereocentres have S-configuration.
A (13)C-modified compound that is carbon dioxide in which the carbon is present as its (13)C isotope.
A 2,2'-lysobisphosphatidic acid in which both acyl groups are specified as oleoyl.
A member of the class of glycerophosphoglycerols obtained by formal condensation  of the carboxy group of oleic acid with one of the primary hydroxy groups of (S,S)-glycero-1-phospho-1'-glycerol
A 1,1'-lysobisphosphatidic acid in which both acyl groups are specified as oleoyl.

An isotopically modified compound in which the abundance of a (14)C isotope at one or more positions has been increased above that of the naturally occurring level (1 - 1.5 atoms for every 10(12) atoms of the carbon in the atmosphere). With a half-life of 5,700 years, (14)C is the longest-lived radioisotope of carbon.
A member of the class of glycerophosphoglycerols obtained by formal condensation of the carboxy group of oleic acid with one of the secondary hydroxy groups of (S,S)-glycero-1-phospho-1'-glycerol

An isotopically modified compound which contains one or more (11)C atoms. (11)C is the most stable artificial isotope of carbon, decaying by positron emission to (11)B with a half-life of 20.334 minutes.

A polyacyl alpha,alpha-trehalose in which the two hydroxy hydrogens at positions 6 and 6' of alpha,alpha-trehalose have been replaced by fatty acyl groups. A 6,6'-diacyltrehalose lipid found in C. elegans dauer larvae.
A chlorophyllide obtained by hydrolysis of the terpenoid ester moiety of any bacteriochlorophyll f.

An iron oxide nanoparticle consisting of a magnetic iron oxide core (usually magnetite, Fe3O4, or maghemite, gamma-Fe2O3). They may be coated with a biocompatible polymer or precipitated within the pores of a porous biocompatible polymer, which can be attached to cytotoxic drugs or antibodies. These can be targeted to the required area using external magnets; after the external magnetic field is removed, the particles no longer show magnetic interaction.
